 than nuclear annihilation. Drawing upon a rich array of declassified documents, movies, and reportage—from national security directives to films like The Manchurian Candidate—his book explores the ways in which east-west disputes over prisoners, repatriation, and defection shaped popular culture. Captivity became a way to understand everything from the anomie of suburban housewives to the "slave world" of drug addiction. Sixty years later, this era may seem distant. Yet, with interrogation techniques derived from America's communist enemies now being used in the "war on terror," the past remains powerfully present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aBrainwashingxHistoryx20th century. 0aBrainwashingxHistoryy20th century. 0aCaptivity narratives. 0aCold War in literature. 0aCold War in mass media. 0aCold War in motion pictures. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aDefectionxHistoryx20th century. 0aDefectionxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical prisonersxHistoryx20th century. 0aPolitical prisonersxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRepatriationxHistoryx20th century. 0aRepatriationxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american history.  a20th century american politics.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  abrainwashing scare.  acaptivity.  acold war mobilization.  acold war.  acommunism.  acommunist enemies.  acultural history.  adefection.  adrug addiction.  aearly cold war america.  agovernment and governing.  agulag consciousness.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  aimprisonment.  aindividual autonomy.  akorean war captivity.  amenticide.  ana